title.value: Instructions for Use

div.p: Keep this leaflet. These instructions show step-by-step directions on how to prepare and give an injection.

title.value: Product Name

div.p: Product Name
(Pro-duct Nay-m)
(generic name)
40 mg/0.8 mL
Injection for subcutaneous
(under the skin) use only

title.value: Storage Information

div.p: Store your PRODUCT NAME pen in the refrigerator at 36°F to 46°F (2°C to 8°C).
Store your PRODUCT NAME pen in the original carton until use to protect from light.
Do not freeze PRODUCT NAME. Do not use PRODUCT NAME if frozen, even if it has been thawed.
Refrigerated PRODUCT NAME may be used until the expiration date printed on the PRODUCT NAME carton or pen. Do not use PRODUCT NAME after the expiration date.

If needed, for example when you are traveling, you may also store PRODUCT NAME at room temperature up to 86°F (30°C) for up to 30 days. Store PRODUCT NAME in the original carton until use to protect it from light.
Throw away PRODUCT NAME if it has been kept at room temperature and not been used within 30 days.
Record the date you first remove PRODUCT NAME from the refrigerator in the spaces provided on the PRODUCT NAME pen carton.
Do not store PRODUCT NAME in extreme heat or cold.
Do not use the pen if the liquid is cloudy, discolored, or has flakes or particles in it.
Keep PRODUCT NAME, injection supplies, and all other medicines out of the reach of children.
PRODUCT NAME for injection comes in a disposable (throw away) single use pen that contains a single dose of medicine.
PRODUCT NAME for injection can be given by a patient, caregiver or healthcare provider.

Do not try to inject PRODUCT NAME yourself until you are shown the right way to give the injections and read and understand the Instructions for Use. If your healthcare provider decides that you or a caregiver may be able to give your injections of PRODUCT NAME at home, you should receive training on the right way to prepare and inject PRODUCT NAME. It is important that you read, understand, and follow these instructions so that you inject PRODUCT NAME the right way.

It is important to talk to your healthcare provider to be sure you understand your PRODUCT NAME dosing instructions. To help you remember when to inject PRODUCT NAME, you can mark your calendar ahead of time. Call your healthcare provider if you or your caregiver have any questions about the right way to inject PRODUCT NAME.

title.value: Step 1: Supplies you need

ul.li: You will need the following supplies for each injection of ABRILADA. Find a clean, flat surface to place the supplies on.
1 ABRILADA pen (included inside the carton)
1 alcohol swab (included inside the carton)
1 cotton ball or gauze pad (not included in your ABRILADA carton)
1 puncture resistant sharps disposal container for pen disposal (not included in your ABRILADA carton). See Step 10 "Dispose of used pen" at the end of this Instructions for Use.

title.value: Step 2: Getting ready

ul.li: Remove the ABRILADA carton from the refrigerator.
Make sure the name ABRILADA appears on the carton and prefilled pen label.
Take out 1 ABRILADA pen and the alcohol swab. Keep your pen out of direct sunlight. Put the original carton with any unused pens back in the refrigerator.

Do not use your pen if:
your pen or the carton containing the pen has been dropped
it has been frozen or thawed
it has been kept in direct sunlight
it appears to be damaged
the seals on a new carton are broken
it has been out of the refrigerator for more than 30 days
the expiration date has passed
the liquid is cloudy, discolored or has flakes or particles
For a more comfortable injection, you may leave your pen at room temperature for 15 to 30 minutes before your injection.
Do not warm ABRILADA in any other way (for example, do not warm it in a microwave or in hot water).
Do not shake your pen. Shaking can damage your medicine.
Wash your hands with soap and water, and dry completely.
Do not remove the cap until you are ready to inject.

title.value: Step 3: Check

ul.li: Look carefully at your medicine in the window.
Make sure the medicine in the pen is clear and colorless to very light brown and free from flakes or particles.
It is normal to see one or more air bubbles in the window.
Check the expiration date on the pen label. The location of the expiration date on the pen label is shown below.

li.p: Do not use the pen if the expiration date has passed.
If you have any questions about your medicine, please contact your healthcare provider or pharmacist.

title.value: Step 4: Check your medicine and expiration date

display.value: Step 4: Check your medicine and expiration date

ul.li:
Choose a different injection site each time you give an injection:
Only use the front of your thighs or your lower abdomen (belly) as shown. If you choose your abdomen, do not use the area 2 inches around your belly button (navel).
Each new injection should be given at least one inch from a site you used before.

Do not inject into bony areas or areas on your skin that are bruised, red, sore (tender) or hard. Avoid injecting into areas with scars or stretch marks.
If you have psoriasis, do not inject directly into any raised, thick, red, or scaly skin patches or lesions on your skin.
Do not inject through your clothes.
Wipe the injection site with the alcohol swab.
Allow the injection site to dry. Do not fan or blow on the clean area.
Do not touch this area again before giving the injection.

title.value: Step 5: Choose and prepare the injection site

display.value: Step 5: Choose and prepare the injection site

ul.li: Twist and pull off the cap.
Throw the cap away into a sharps disposal container. You will not need it again.

div.p: Important: Handle your pen with care to avoid an accidental needle stick injury.
Note: A needle cover stays inside the cap after cap removal.

title.value: Step 6: Remove the cap

ul.li: Push your pen firmly against the skin at 90 degrees, as shown in the diagram.

div.p: Note: The needle goes into the skin as you push your pen down. You will only be able to press down the injection button in Step 7 when you are pushing down firmly enough.

ul.li: Keep your pen pushed against the skin until Step 9.

title.value: Step 7: Insert the needle

ul.li: Press the injection button all the way down and you will hear a click. The click means the start of the injection.
Keep holding your pen firmly against the skin while the orange bar moves across the window. You will hear a 2nd click.
Wait for at least 5 more seconds after the 2nd click to make sure you get the full dose of medicine.

div.p: Note: If you cannot press down the injection button, it is because you are not pushing the pen down firmly enough at the injection site. See the Question and Answer section on the right side of this Instructions for Use for more information on what to do if the injection button does not press down.

title.value: Step 8: Inject your medicine

ul.li: You should see an orange bar in the window.
Do not remove your pen until you have waited at least 5 seconds after the 2nd click and until the orange bar completely fills the window.

title.value: Step 9: Check the window

ul.li: Remove your pen from the skin.

div.p: Note: After you remove your pen from the skin, the needle will be automatically covered.

ul.li: If the window has not turned orange, this means you have not received a full dose. Call your healthcare provider or pharmacist right away.
Do not inject another dose.

title.value: Step 10: Remove the pen

ul.li: Put your used pen in a FDA-cleared sharps disposal container right away after use. Do not throw away (dispose of) pens in your household trash.

If you do not have a FDA-cleared sharps disposal container, you may use a household container that is:
made of heavy duty plastic,
can be closed with a tight-fitting, puncture-resistant lid, without sharps being able to come out,
upright and stable during use,
leak-resistant, and
is properly labeled to warn of hazardous waste inside the container.

When your sharps disposal container is almost full, you will need to follow your community guidelines for the right way to dispose of your sharps disposal container. There may be state or local laws about how you should throw away used needles and syringes. For more information about safe sharps disposal, and for specific information about sharps disposal in the state that you live in, go to the FDA's website at http://www.fda.gov/safesharpsdisposal.
Do not dispose of your used sharps disposal container in your household trash unless your community guidelines permit this. Do not recycle your used sharps disposal container.

title.value: Step 11: Dispose of used pen

ul.li: Look closely at your injection site. If there is blood, use a clean cotton ball or gauze pad to press lightly on the injection area for a few seconds.
Do not rub the injection site.

div.p: Note: Store any unused pens in the refrigerator in the original carton.

title.value: Questions and Answers
What should I do with my pen if it has been dropped?

display.value: What should I do with my pen if it has been dropped?

div.p: Do not use it, even if it looks undamaged. Dispose of your pen in the same way as a used pen. You will need to use a new pen to give your injection.

title.value: Can I use my pen straight from the refrigerator?

display.value: Can I use my pen straight from the refrigerator?

div.p: Yes, however you may find that using the pen at room temperature reduces stinging or discomfort. If you allow your pen to reach room temperature before use, you must keep it away from direct sunlight as this can damage your medicine.

title.value: What should I do if I need to travel?

display.value: What should I do if I need to travel?

div.p: When you are traveling, you may store your pen in its carton at room temperature up to 86°F (30°C) for up to 30 days.

title.value: Is it okay to shake my pen before I use it?

display.value: Is it okay to shake my pen before I use it?

div.p: No, do not shake your pen. Shaking can damage your medicine. When you check your medicine, gently tilt your pen back and forth while looking carefully into the window. It is normal to see one or more air bubbles.

title.value: Do I need to remove any air bubbles before using my pen?

display.value: Do I need to remove any air bubbles before using my pen?

div.p: No, do not attempt to remove air bubbles.

title.value: Drops of medicine have appeared at the needle tip. Is this okay?

display.value: Drops of medicine have appeared at the needle tip. Is this okay?

div.p: Yes, it is normal to see a few drops of medicine at the needle tip when you remove the cap.

title.value: Can I re-insert the needle if I change my mind where I want to inject?

display.value: Can I re-insert the needle if I change my mind where I want to inject?

div.p: No, you should not re-insert the needle into your skin. If you change your mind, you will need a replacement pen if the needle has already been inserted into the skin. After the injection button has been pressed, you must not lift your pen from the skin until the injection has finished.

title.value: I pushed my pen against the skin but could not press the button down. What should I do?

display.value: I pushed my pen against the skin but could not press the button down. What should I do?

div.p: Take your finger off the injection button and push your pen down more firmly against the skin. Then try pushing the button again. If this does not work, stretching the skin may make the injection site firmer, making pressing the injection button easier.

title.value: Can I pinch or stretch the skin at the injection area?

display.value: Can I pinch or stretch the skin at the injection area?

div.p: Yes, pinching or stretching the skin before injection may make the injection site firmer, making it easier to press the injection button.

title.value: Do I need to keep my finger pressed on the injection button for the whole injection?

display.value: Do I need to keep my finger pressed on the injection button for the whole injection?

div.p: No, you can stop pressing the button when the injection has started. However, make sure you keep holding the pen firmly against the skin. The pen will continue to deliver your medicine.

title.value: How long will the injection take?

display.value: How long will the injection take?

div.p: From the time the dose begins until you hear the 2nd click, it usually takes 3 to 10 seconds. After the 2nd click, you should continue to hold your pen in place for at least 5 more seconds to make sure you give the full dose.

title.value: What should I do if I see more than a small drop of medicine on the skin after giving my injection?

display.value: What should I do if I see more than a small drop of medicine on the skin after giving my injection?

div.p: Nothing this time, but for your next injection wait a little longer before removing the pen from the skin to make sure all of the medicine went into your skin.

title.value: What should I do if I have any questions about my ABRILADA pen or medicine?

display.value: What should I do if I have any questions about my ABRILADA pen or medicine?

div.p: Contact your healthcare provider or pharmacist.
This Instructions for Use has been approved by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration.
